For the analysis, an annulus of two concentric cylinders of infinite length, inner radius, R1 , and outer radius, R2 , as shown in Figure 1, are considered. Fluid is flowing in the axial (z) direction, while the flow is influenced by the inner cylindrical rod, moving axially at constant velocity U. The flow is considered to be hydro-dynamically fully developed. No slip boundary conditions are assumed to be valid at both the plates for both hydro-dynamically and thermally developed flows. For the thermal boundary conditions, the case is considered where inner and outer walls of the annulus are at different (unequal) constant temperatures, T1 and T2 , respectively. In addition to considering the flow to be fully developed (hydro-dynamically), some other assumptions considered for the study are given below:
Newtonian fluid;
incompressible fluid flow;
no heat generation and constant thermo-physical properties;
negligible axial conduction in the fluid and through the wall
